The first `<div>` has the following properties:

```
border-bottom-left-radius: 20px;
border-bottom-right-radius: 20px;
border-top-left-radius: 20px;
border-top-right-radius: 20px;
display: block;
grid-column-end: auto;
grid-column-start: span 12;
grid-row-end: auto;
grid-row-start: span 2;
height: 120px;
position: relative;
width: 500px;
```

`<hui-card>` has the following properties:

```
display: inline;
grid.container	User Agent Style Sheet
height: auto;
width: auto;
```

And `<calendar-card-pro-dev ...>` has these properties:

```
display: block;
block:host	User Agent Style Sheet
grid.container	User Agent Style Sheet
height: 293px;
width: 500px;
```

As you can see, the calendar-card itself has a height of 293px while the div only is 120px high, which equals 2 rows with 60px each. Therefore, as soon as `grid_options.rows` is set to any number in our card's config, this setting has to override every other height definition. We could implement a precedence or priority order in our code. As soon as `grid_options.rows`is defined, we could also calculate the height with `60px * grid_options.rows`, if there is no automatic way to let our card's content auto-scale to the div height (while not exceeding it).

Please do a thorough research how native HA cards implement this and come back with a proposed implementation that fixes the issue.

